			"contents": "In a group project, what role do you typically take on?\nIn a group, I usually don't try to interfere unless I see the project going off course. While I admit this is not the most active role, I have found oin my experience that allowing the group to naturally walk through and settle on and idea they believe to be their own helps with group cohesion as well as motivation to push through, even when the solution may not be most optimal. In fact, in cases where a strong leader rises and takes control, I have found that when things go wrong, it becomes very easy for the group to lose motivation. In contrast if the group, through stimulated and ocassionally assisted discussion reaches a consensus on their own, they are much more likely to persist through hardship.\n\nHow do you approach a situation where someone in a group project isn't pulling their weight? \nIn situations like this, they simply have not found something they want to help with. Fortunately, in cohorts such as this, people generally engage in good faith. This ties back into the answer from problem 1, as if they had input in designing the solution, they are much more motivated. But in the case that they aren't motivated, having them work on a separate part by themselves works really really well, and they often merge back into the larger group as they geniunely want to work with others.\n\nHow do you prioritize your time at school when you have many tasks and not enough time, especially under times of stress?\n\nHow do you spend your free time? \n\nIn the internship, what are you most interested in on working on? Core LLM development, front end, product work, etc.?\n\n",
